```{r, include = FALSE}
knitr::opts_chunk$set(
  collapse = TRUE,
  comment = "#>"
)
```


## Connecting to the database
```{r setup}
library(renmods)
library(lubridate)
```


Download/update the data and save to your cache.

```{r}
#| eval: false
renmods_update(type = "all")
```


Connect to the database ENMODS table

```{r}
db <- renmods_connect()
```

Optionally, prefilter by data type or date range.

```{r}
db <- renmods_connect(type = "this_yr")
db <- renmods_connect(dates = c("2024-12-15", "2025-01-15"))
db <- renmods_connect(dates = c("2026-01-01", "2026-01-31"))
```


## Collecting data into memory

Collect the data into a data frame (from a database connection) for working/saving.
The smaller the data set and the fewer data types, the fast this will go.

```{r}
df <- collect(db)
```

Or use the dplyr package to do more filtering before you collect the data.

```{r}
#| message: false
library(dplyr)
```

First we'll check out what's in the data by exploring the first couple data points
```{r}
glimpse(db)
```

Remind yourself of the column names
```{r}
colnames(db)
```

Now we can filter by column values and collect the data into R
```{r}
df <- db |>
  filter(Location_ID %in% c("E303052", "E309247")) |>
  collect()

df
```

You can also pre-select your columns of interest.

```{r}
df <- db |>
  filter(Location_ID %in% c("E303052", "E309247")) |>
  select(
    "Location_ID",
    "Location_Name",
    "ren_date",
    "ren_tz",
    "Observed_Date_Time",
    "Observed_Property_Name",
    "Result_Value",
    "Result_Unit",
    "Analysis_Method_ID"
  ) |>
  collect()

df
```

## Dates and Times

ENMODS stores date/times as character/text fields with the timezone indicated by +/- offset (e.g., '-08:00'). However, in R all values in a column must use the same timezone. Therefore renmods converts times to UTC-7:00
(called `Etc/GMT+7`, note that `+` is correct; see the [Wikipedia page on
timezones](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_tz_database_time_zones#List)).

This may not be always ideal depending on the region you're working in, so 
the original timezone from `Observed_Date_Time` is stored in a new field `ren_tz`
for reference. You can convert to any timezone using the [lubridate::with_tz()](https://lubridate.tidyverse.org/reference/with_tz.html) function.

We can see that we're in UTC -7 by looking at the first couple of values.
```{r}
df$Observed_Date_Time[1:5]
```

If we want to be in UTC -6:00 we can convert with lubridate's `with_tz()` function.

```{r}
with_tz(df$Observed_Date_Time[1:5], tz = "Etc/GMT+6")
```

This only converts the first 5 observations, just for illustration.

If we want to convert the entire data frame to Mountain time (including DST depending on the time of year),
we could use the `America/Edmonton` timezone.

```{r}
df_tz <- mutate(
  df,
  Observed_Date_Time = with_tz(Observed_Date_Time, "America/Edmonton")
)
# Take a look:
df_tz$Observed_Date_Time[1:5]
```

If you wanted to convert all time columns at once, you could use the `across()`
function from dplyr.

First we'll get the whole data set again
```{r}
df <- renmods_connect(dates = c("2024-12-15", "2025-01-15")) |>
  collect()
```

What time columns do we have?
```{r}
select(df, contains("Time"))
```

We can use the tidyselector `contains()` with across to apply a function *across* a series of columns.
```{r}
df_tz <- mutate(
  df,
  across(contains("Time"), \(col) with_tz(col, "America/Edmonton"))
)

# Take a look:
df_tz$Observed_Date_Time[1:5]
df_tz$Field_Visit_Start_Time[1:5]
```

## Disconnecting

Don't forget to close the connection to the database

```{r}
renmods_disconnect(db)
```